# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: serial-digital-interface
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:serial-digital-interface/180-line-television-system] The Berlin Summer Olympic Games were televised, using both closed-circuit 375-line fully electronic iconoscope-based cameras and 180-line intermediate film cameras transmitting to Berlin, Hamburg, Munich, Nuremberg, and Bayreuth via special Reichspost long-distance cables in August 1936.
[src:serial-digital-interface/180-line-television-system] In Berlin, twenty-eight public 180-line television rooms were opened for anybody who did not own a television set.
[src:serial-digital-interface/180-line-television-system] After February 1937, both 180- and 375-line systems were replaced by a superior, 441-line system.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] TV cameras were based on the iconoscope, the primary camera tube used in American broadcasting from 1936 until 1946, when it was replaced by the image orthicon tube.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] Earlier cameras used special spotlights or spinning disks to capture light from a single very brightly lit spot, and were not suitable for broadcasting of outdoor live events.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] This early standard was soon replaced by 441-line systems.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] 343-line broadcasts where introduced by RCA and NBC on November 6, 1936.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] Tests started the previous year from New York City (W2XF on the Empire State Building), where NBC converted a radio studio in the Rockefeller Center for television use.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] Several prototype TV sets were produced by RCA in 1936, but none was available commercially.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] Broadcasts were limited to public demonstrations in New York City (RCA) and Philadelphia (Philco) - to be exact, Philco demonstrated a 345-line system, but in practice both systems were identical.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] The 343-line system was proposed for FCC approval by the Radio Manufacturers Association (RMA) in December 1937.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] Broadcasts were phased out the following year, in favor of a 441-line system.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] A a similar 343-line system was tested in the Soviet Union (Moscow) from 1937 onwards.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] RCA provided broadcast equipment and documentation for the TV sets, that were then produced locally.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] The system was adapted for 50 Hz mains electricity, with a field rate of 50 Hz.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] The first experimental transmissions happened on March 9, 1937, followed by regular broadcasts on December 31, 1938.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] In 1939, a 343-line system was under development in Poland, publicly demonstrated during the Warsaw Radio Exhibition on August.
[src:serial-digital-interface/343-line-television-system] Regular operations were planned for the beginning of 1940, but work stopped due to the outbreak of World War II.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] 375-line (50 fps, interlaced) television was demonstrated in 1936 on the Berlin Funkausstellung.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] The system used electronic cameras for live exterior broadcasts.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] The system was also used on experimental transmissions of the 1936 Summer Olympics (along with the 180-line system), using the Telefunken Iconoscope camera.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] A transmitter was setup in Berlin-Witzleben, broadcasting at 42.9 MHz.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] The Reichspost distributed the signal to major cities across Germany using cables.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] After the Games transmissions continued to viewing rooms installed on post offices.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] Philips presented a radio/TV combo receiver for the system at the 1937 Berlin Funkausstellung, and Loewe also had a receiver available.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] In the same year Telefunken demonstrated the 375-line system at the Paris Exposition Internationale des Arts et Techniques dans la Vie Moderne, displaying images taken from the exhibition's pavilion terrace.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] In Italy 375-line television transmissions were undertaken by Arturo Castellani in 1937, with daily broadcasts from Rome, between 6pm and 9:30pm on 6.9 meters (43.45 MHz) with a power of 2 kW.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] In the spring of 1940, CBS staff engineer Peter Goldmark devised a system for color television, hoping to gain advantage regarding NBC and its black-and-white RCA system.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] The new system proposed by CBS was based on field sequential color and incompatible with existing sets but "gave brilliant and stable colors", while NBC developed a black and white compatible color TV system that was "crude and unstable but compatible".
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] The system was tested from CBS station WCBW New York, on June 1, 1941.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] In 1945 CBS demonstrates color broadcast using test equipment and a 10 MHz bandwidth UHF channel.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] Eventually it was shown to the general public on January 12, 1950, as the 405-line Field-Sequential Color System (FSC).
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] The vertical resolution was 77% of monochrome, and the horizontal resolution was 54% of monochrome.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] The Federal Communications Commission adopted it on October 11, 1950, as the standard for color television in the United States, but it was later withdrawn.
[src:serial-digital-interface/375-line-television-system] The concept was revived by NASA in 1969 for the Apollo color TV cameras.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The basic components of 3D film were introduced separately between 1833 and 1839.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Stroboscopic animation was developed by Joseph Plateau in 1832 and published in 1833 in the form of a stroboscopic disc, which he later called the fantascope and became better known as the phénakisticope.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Around the very same time (1832/1833), Charles Wheatstone developed the stereoscope, but he did not really make it public before June 1838.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The first practical forms of photography were introduced in January 1839 by Louis Daguerre and Henry Fox Talbot.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] A combination of these elements into animated stereoscopic photography may have been conceived early on, but for decades it did not become possible to capture motion in real-time photographic recordings due to the long exposure times necessary for the light-sensitive emulsions that were used.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Charles Wheatstone got inventor Henry Fox Talbot to produce some calotype pairs for the stereoscope and received the first results in October 1840.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Only a few more experimental stereoscopic photographs were made before David Brewster introduced his stereoscope with lenses in 1849.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Wheatstone also approached Joseph Plateau with the suggestion to combine the stereoscope with the fantascope.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In 1849, Plateau published about this concept in an article about several improvements made to his fantascope and suggested a stop-motion technique that would involve a series of photographs of purpose-made plaster statuettes in different poses.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The idea reached Jules Duboscq, an instrument maker who already marketed Plateau's Fantascope as well as the stereoscopes of Wheatstone and Brewster.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In November 1852, Duboscq added the concept of his "Stéréoscope-fantascope, ou Bïoscope" to his stereoscope patent.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Production of images proved very difficult, since the photographic sequence had to be carefully constructed from separate still images.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The bioscope was no success, and the only extant disc, without apparatus, is found in the Joseph Plateau collection of the University of Ghent.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The disc contains 12 albumen image pairs of a machine in motion.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Most other early attempts to create motion pictures also aimed to include stereoscopic effects.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In November 1851, Antoine Claudet claimed to have created a stereoscope that showed people in motion.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The device initially only showed two phases, but during the next two years, Claudet worked on a camera that would record stereoscopic pairs for four different poses (patented in 1853).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Claudet found that the stereoscopic effect did not work properly in this device, but believed the illusion of motion was successful.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In 1855, Johann Nepomuk Czermak published an article about his Stereophoroskop.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] His first idea to create 3D animation involved sticking pins in a stroboscopic disc to create a sequence that would show one pin moving further into the cardboard and back.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] He also designed a device that would feed the image pairs from two stroboscopic discs into one lenticular stereoscope and a vertical predecessor of the zoetrope.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] On February 27, 1860, Peter Hubert Desvignes received British patent no.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] 537 for 28 monocular and stereoscopic variations of cylindrical stroboscopic devices.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] This included a version that used an endless band of pictures running between two spools that was intermittently lit by an electric spark.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Desvignes' *Mimoscope*, received an Honourable Mention "for ingenuity of construction" at the 1862 International Exhibition in London.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In 1861, American engineer Coleman Sellers II received US patent No.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] 35,317 for the kinematoscope, a device that exhibited "stereoscopic pictures as to make them represent objects in motion".
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In his application he stated: "This has frequently been done with plane pictures but has never been, with stereoscopic pictures".
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] He used three sets of stereoscopic photographs in a sequence with some duplicates to regulate the flow of a simple repetitive motion, but also described a system for very large series of pictures of complicated motion.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] On August 11, 1877, the *Daily Alta* newspaper announced a project by Eadward Muybridge and Leland Stanford to produce sequences of photographs of a running horse with 12 stereoscopic cameras.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Muybridge had much experience with stereo photography and had already made instantaneous pictures of Stanford's horse Occident running at full speed.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] He eventually managed to shoot the proposed sequences of running horses in June 1878 with stereoscopic cameras.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Thomas Edison demonstrated his phonograph on November 29, 1877, after previous announcements of the device for recording and replaying sound had been published earlier in the year.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] An article in *Scientific American* concluded, "It is already possible, by ingenious optical contrivances, to throw stereoscopic photographs of people on screens in full view of an audience.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Add the talking phonograph to counterfeit their voices, and it would be difficult to carry the illusion of real presence much further".
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Wordsworth Donisthorpe announced in the January 24, 1878, edition of *Nature* that he would advance that conception: "By combining the phonograph with the kinesigraph, I will undertake not only to produce a talking picture of Mr.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Gladstone, which, with motionless lips and unchanged expression, shall positively recite his latest anti-Turkish speech in his own voice and tone.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Not only this, but the life size photograph itself shall move and gesticulate precisely as he did when making the speech, the words and gestures corresponding as in real life." Dr.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Phipson, a correspondent for British news in a French photography magazine, relayed the concept but renamed the device "Kinétiscope" to reflect the viewing purpose rather than the recording option.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] This was picked up in the United States and discussed in an interview with Edison later in the year.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Neither Donisthorpe's nor Edison's later moving picture results were stereoscopic.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In the late 1890s, British film pioneer William Friese-Greene filed a patent for a 3D film process.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In his patent, two films were projected side by side on screen.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The viewer looked through a stereoscope to converge the two images.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Because of the obtrusive mechanics behind this method, theatrical use was not practical.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Frederic Eugene Ives patented his stereo camera rig in 1900.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The camera had two lenses positioned 1+3⁄4 inches (4.45 centimeters) apart.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Waddell presented tests to an audience at the Astor Theater in New York City.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] However, according to Adolph Zukor in his 1953 autobiography *The Public Is Never Wrong: My 50 Years in the Motion Picture Industry*, nothing was produced in this process after these tests.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] By 1909, the German film market suffered much from overproduction and too much competition.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] German film tycoon Oskar Messter had initially gained much financial success with the Tonbild synchronized sound films of his Biophon system since 1903, but the films were losing money by the end of the decade, and Messter would stop Tonbild production in 1913.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Producers and exhibitors were looking into new film attractions and invested for instance in colorful imagery.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The development of stereoscopic cinema seemed a logical step to lure visitors back into the movie theaters.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In 1909, German civil engineer August Engelsmann patented a process that projected filmed performances within a physical decor on an actual stage.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Soon after, Messter obtained patents for a very similar process, probably by agreement with Engelsmann, and started marketing it as "Alabastra".
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Performers were brightly dressed and brightly lit while filmed against a black background, mostly miming their singing or musical skills or dancing to the circa four-minute pre-recorded phonographs.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The film recordings would be projected from below, to appear as circa 30 inch figures on a glass pane in front of a small stage, in a setup very similar to the Pepper's ghost illusion that offered a popular stage trick technique since the 1860s.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The glass pane was not visible to the audience and the projected figures seemed able to move around freely across the stage in their virtual tangible and lifelike appearance.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The brightness of the figures was necessary to avoid see-through spots and made them resemble alabaster sculptures.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] To adapt to this appearance, several films featured Pierrot or other white clowns, while some films were probably hand-coloured.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Although Alabastra was well received by the press, Messter produced few titles, hardly promoted them and abandoned it altogether a few years later.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] He believed the system to be uneconomical due to its need for special theatres instead of the widely available movie screens, and he did not like that it seemed only suitable for stage productions and not for "natural" films.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Nonetheless, there were numerous imitators in Germany and Messter and Engelsmann still teamed with American businessman Frank Joseph Godsol (Goldsoll) set up a short-lived variant named "Fantomo" in 1914.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Rather in agreement with Messter or not, Karl Juhasz and Franz Haushofer opened a Kinoplastikon theatre in Vienna in 1911.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Their patented system was very similar to Alabaster, but projected life-size figures from the wings of the stage.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] With much higher ticket prices than standard cinema, it was targeted at middle-class audiences to fill the gap between low-brow films and high-class theatre.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Audiences reacted enthusiastically and by 1913 there reportedly were 250 theatres outside Austria, in France, Italy, United Kingdom, Russia and North America.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] However, the first Kinoplastikon in Paris started in January 1914 and the premiere in New York took place in the Hippodrome in March 1915.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Kinoplastikon, presumably in collaboration with Cecil Hepworth.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Theodore Brown, the licensee in the U.K. also patented a variant with front and back projection and reflected decor, and Goldsoll applied for a very similar patent only 10 days later.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Further development and exploitation was probably halted by World War I.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Alabastra and Kinoplastikon were often advertised as stereoscopic and screenless.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Eventually, longer (multi-reel) films with story arcs proved to be the way out of the crisis in the movie market and supplanted the previously popular short films that mostly aimed to amuse people with tricks, gags or other brief variety and novelty attractions.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Sound film, stereoscopic film and other novel techniques were relatively cumbersome to combine with multiple reels and were abandoned for a while.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The earliest confirmed 3D film shown to an out-of-house audience was *The Power of Love*, which premiered at the Ambassador Hotel Theater in Los Angeles on September 27, 1922.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The camera rig was a product of the film's producer, Harry K.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] It was filmed dual-strip in black and white, and single strip color anaglyphic release prints were produced using a color film invented and patented by Harry K.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] A single projector could be used to display the movie but anaglyph glasses were used for viewing.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The camera system and special color release print film all received U.S Patent No.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] After a preview for exhibitors and press in New York City, the film dropped out of sight, apparently not booked by exhibitors, and is now considered lost.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Early in December 1922, William Van Doren Kelley, inventor of the Prizma color system, cashed in on the growing interest in 3D films started by Fairall's demonstration and shot footage with a camera system of his own design.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Kelley then struck a deal with Samuel "Roxy" Rothafel to premiere the first in his series of "Plasticon" shorts entitled *Movies of the Future* at the Rivoli Theater in New York City.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Also in December 1922, Laurens Hammond (later inventor of the Hammond organ) premiered his Teleview system, which had been shown to the trade and press in October.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Teleview was the first alternating-frame 3D system seen by the public.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Using left-eye and right-eye prints and two interlocked projectors, left and right frames were alternately projected, each pair being shown three times to suppress flicker.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Viewing devices attached to the armrests of the theater seats had rotary shutters that operated synchronously with the projector shutters, producing a clean and clear stereoscopic result.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The only theater known to have installed Teleview was the Selwyn Theater in New York City, and only one show was ever presented with it: a group of short films, an exhibition of live 3D shadows, and *M.A.R.S.*, the only Teleview feature.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The show ran for several weeks, apparently doing good business as a novelty (*M.A.R.S.* itself got poor reviews), but Teleview was never seen again.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In 1922, Frederic Eugene Ives and Jacob Leventhal began releasing their first stereoscopic shorts made over a three-year period.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The first film, entitled *Plastigrams*, was distributed nationally by Educational Pictures in the red-and-blue anaglyph format.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Ives and Leventhal then went on to produce the following stereoscopic shorts in the "Stereoscopiks Series" released by Pathé Films in 1925: *Zowie* (April 10), *Luna-cy!* (May 18), *The Run-Away Taxi* (December 17) and *Ouch* (December 17).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] On September 22, 1924, *Luna-cy!* was re-released in the De Forest Phonofilm sound-on-film system.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The late 1920s to early 1930s saw little interest in stereoscopic pictures.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In Paris, Louis Lumiere shot footage with his stereoscopic camera in September 1933.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The following March he exhibited a remake of his 1895 short film *L'Arrivée du Train*, this time in anaglyphic 3D, at a meeting of the French Academy of Science.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In 1936, Leventhal and John Norling were hired based on their test footage to film MGM's *Audioscopiks* series.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The prints were by Technicolor in the red-and-green anaglyph format, and were narrated by Pete Smith.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The first film, *Audioscopiks*, premiered January 11, 1936, and *The New Audioscopiks* premiered January 15, 1938.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] *Audioscopiks* was nominated for the Academy Award in the category Best Short Subject, Novelty in 1936.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] With the success of the two Audioscopiks films, MGM produced one more short in anaglyph 3D, another Pete Smith Specialty called *Third Dimensional Murder* (1941).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Unlike its predecessors, this short was shot with a studio-built camera rig.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Prints were by Technicolor in red-and-blue anaglyph.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The short is notable for being one of the few live-action appearances of the Frankenstein Monster as conceived by Jack Pierce for Universal Studios outside of their company.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] While many of these films were printed by color systems, none of them was actually in color, and the use of the color printing was only to achieve an anaglyph effect.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] While attending Harvard University, Edwin H.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Land conceived the idea of reducing glare by polarizing light.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] He took a leave of absence from Harvard to set up a lab and by 1929 had invented and patented a polarizing sheet.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In 1932, he introduced **Polaroid J Sheet** as a commercial product.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] While his original intention was to create a filter for reducing glare from car headlights, Land did not underestimate the utility of his newly dubbed Polaroid filters in stereoscopic presentations.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In February 1936, Land gave the first public demonstration of Polaroid filters in conjunction with 3D photography at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The reaction was enthusiastic, and Land followed it up with an installation at the New York Museum of Science.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] It is unknown what film was run for audiences at this exhibition.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Using Polaroid filters meant an entirely new form of projection, however.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Two prints, each carrying either the right or left eye view, had to be synced up in projection using an external selsyn motor.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Furthermore, polarized light would be largely depolarized by a matte white screen, and only a silver screen or screen made of other reflective material would correctly reflect the separate images.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Later that year, the feature, *Nozze Vagabonde* appeared in Italy, followed in Germany by *Zum Greifen nah* (*You Can Nearly Touch It*), and again in 1939 with Germany's *Sechs Mädel rollen ins Wochenend* (*Six Girls Drive Into the Weekend*).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The Italian film was made with the Gualtierotti camera; the two German productions with the Zeiss camera and the Vierling shooting system.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] All of these films were the first exhibited using Polaroid filters.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The Zeiss Company in Germany manufactured glasses on a commercial basis commencing in 1936; they were also independently made around the same time in Germany by E.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In 1939, John Norling shot *In Tune With Tomorrow*, the first commercial 3D film using Polaroid in the US.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] This short premiered at the 1939 New York World's Fair and was created specifically for the Chrysler Motors Pavilion.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In it, a full 1939 Chrysler Plymouth is magically put together, set to music.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Originally in black and white, the film was so popular that it was re-shot in color for the following year at the fair, under the title *New Dimensions*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In 1953, it was reissued by RKO as *Motor Rhythm*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Another early short that utilized the Polaroid 3D process was 1940's *Magic Movies: Thrills For You* produced by the Pennsylvania Railroad Co. for the Golden Gate International Exposition.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Produced by John Norling, it was filmed by Jacob Leventhal using his own rig.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] It consisted of shots of various views that could be seen from the Pennsylvania Railroad's trains.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] In the 1940s, World War II prioritized military applications of stereoscopic photography and it once again went on the back burner in most producers' minds.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] What aficionados consider the "golden era" of 3D began in late 1952 with the release of the first color stereoscopic feature, *Bwana Devil*, produced, written and directed by Arch Oboler.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The film was shot in "Natural Vision", a process that was co-created and controlled by M.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Gunzberg, who built the rig with his brother Julian, Friend Baker and Lothrop Worth, shopped it without success to various studios before Oboler used it for this feature, which went into production with the title, *The Lions of Gulu*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The critically panned film was nevertheless highly successful with audiences due to the novelty of 3D, which increased Hollywood interest in 3D during a period that had seen declining box-office admissions.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] As with practically all of the features made during this boom, *Bwana Devil* was projected dual-strip, with Polaroid filters.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] During the 1950s, the familiar disposable anaglyph glasses made of cardboard were mainly used for comic books, two shorts by exploitation specialist Dan Sonney, and three shorts produced by Lippert Productions.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] However, even the Lippert shorts were available in the dual-strip format alternatively.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Because the features utilized two projectors, the capacity limit of film being loaded onto each projector (about 6,000 feet (1,800 m), or an hour's worth of film) meant that an intermission was necessary for every feature-length film.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Quite often, intermission points were written into the script at a major plot point.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] During Christmas of 1952, producer Sol Lesser quickly premiered the dual-strip showcase called *Stereo Techniques* in Chicago.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Lesser acquired the rights to five dual-strip shorts.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Two of them, *Now is the Time (to Put On Your Glasses)* and *Around is Around*, were directed by Norman McLaren in 1951 for the National Film Board of Canada.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The other three films were produced in Britain for The Festival of Britain in 1951 by Raymond Spottiswoode.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] These were *A Solid Explanation*, *Royal River*, and *The Black Swan*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] James Mage was also an early pioneer in the 3D craze.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Using his 16 mm 3D Bolex system, he premiered his *Triorama* program on February 10, 1953, with his four shorts: *Sunday In Stereo*, *Indian Summer*, *American Life*, and *This is Bolex Stereo*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Another early 3D film during the boom was the Lippert Productions short *A Day in the Country*, narrated by Joe Besser, which was composed mostly of test footage.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Unlike all of the other Lippert shorts, which were available in both dual-strip and anaglyph, this production was released in anaglyph only.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] April 1953 saw two groundbreaking features in 3D: Columbia's *Man in the Dark* and Warner Bros.' *House of Wax*, the first 3D feature with stereophonic sound.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The success of these two films proved that major studios now had a method of getting filmgoers back into theaters and away from television sets, which were causing a steady decline in attendance.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Universal-International released its first 3D feature, *It Came from Outer Space*, on May 27, 1953, with stereophonic sound.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] That was followed by Paramount's first 3D feature, *Sangaree* with Fernando Lamas and Arlene Dahl.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The Walt Disney Studios entered 3D with its May 28, 1953, release of *Melody*, which accompanied the first 3D western, Columbia's *Fort Ti* at its Los Angeles opening.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] It was later shown at Disneyland's Fantasyland Theater in 1957 as part of a program with Disney's other short *Working for Peanuts*, entitled, *3-D Jamboree*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The show was hosted by the Mousketeers and was in color.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Columbia released several 3D westerns produced by Sam Katzman and directed by William Castle.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Castle would later specialize in various technical in-theater gimmicks for such Columbia and Allied Artists features as *13 Ghosts*, *House on Haunted Hill*, and *The Tingler*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Columbia also produced the only slapstick comedies conceived for 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The Three Stooges starred in *Spooks* and *Pardon My Backfire*; dialect comic Harry Mimmo starred in *Down the Hatch*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Producer Jules White was optimistic about the possibilities of 3D as applied to slapstick (with pies and other projectiles aimed at the audience), but only two of his stereoscopic shorts were shown in 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] *Down the Hatch* was released as a conventional, "flat" motion picture.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] John Ireland, Joanne Dru and Macdonald Carey starred in the Jack Broder color production *Hannah Lee*, which premiered on June 19, 1953.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The film was directed by Ireland, who sued Broder for his salary.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Broder counter-sued, claiming that Ireland went over production costs with the film.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Another famous entry in the golden era of 3D was the 3 Dimensional Pictures production of *Robot Monster*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The film was allegedly scribed in an hour by screenwriter Wyott Ordung and filmed in a period of two weeks on a shoestring budget.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Despite these shortcomings and the fact that the crew had no previous experience with the newly built camera rig, luck was on the cinematographer's side, as many find the 3D photography in the film is well shot and aligned.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] *Robot Monster* also has a notable score by then up-and-coming composer Elmer Bernstein.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The film was released June 24, 1953, and went out with the short *Stardust in Your Eyes*, which starred nightclub comedian, Slick Slavin.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] 20th Century Fox produced its only 3D feature, *Inferno*, in 1953, starring Rhonda Fleming.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Fleming, who also starred in *Those Redheads From Seattle*, and *Jivaro*, shares the spot for being the actress to appear in the most 3D features with Patricia Medina, who starred in *Sangaree*, *Phantom of the Rue Morgue* and *Drums of Tahiti*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] Zanuck expressed little interest in stereoscopic systems, and at that point was preparing to premiere the new widescreen film system, CinemaScope.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p01] The first decline in the theatrical 3D craze started in August and September 1953.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Sol Lesser attempted to follow up *Stereo Techniques* with a new showcase, this time five shorts that he himself produced.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The project was to be called *The 3-D Follies* and was to be distributed by RKO.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Unfortunately, because of financial difficulties and the general loss of interest in 3D, Lesser canceled the project during the summer of 1953, making it the first 3D film to be aborted in production.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Two of the three shorts were shot: *Carmenesque*, a burlesque number starring exotic dancer Lili St.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Cyr, and *Fun in the Sun*, a sports short directed by famed set designer/director William Cameron Menzies, who also directed the 3D feature *The Maze* for Allied Artists.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Although it was more expensive to install, the major competing realism process was wide-screen, but two-dimensional, anamorphic, first utilized by Fox with CinemaScope and its September premiere in *The Robe*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Anamorphic films needed only a single print, so synchronization was not an issue.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Cinerama was also a competitor from the start and had better quality control than 3D because it was owned by one company that focused on quality control.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] However, most of the 3D features past the summer of 1953 were released in the flat widescreen formats ranging from 1.66:1 to 1.85:1.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In early studio advertisements and articles about widescreen and 3D formats, widescreen systems were referred to as "3D", causing some confusion among scholars.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] There was no single instance of combining CinemaScope with 3D until 1960, with a film called *September Storm*, and even then, that was a blow-up from a non-anamorphic negative.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] *September Storm* also went out with the last dual-strip short, *Space Attack*, which was actually shot in 1954 under the title *The Adventures of Sam Space*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In December 1953, 3D made a comeback with the release of several important 3D films, including MGM's musical *Kiss Me, Kate*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] *Kate* was the hill over which 3D had to pass to survive.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] MGM tested it in six theaters: three in 3D and three-flat.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] According to trade ads of the time, the 3D version was so well-received that the film quickly went into a wide stereoscopic release.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] However, most publications, including Kenneth Macgowan's classic film reference book *Behind the Screen*, state that the film did much better as a "regular" release.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The film, adapted from the popular Cole Porter Broadway musical, starred the MGM songbird team of Howard Keel and Kathryn Grayson as the leads, supported by Ann Miller, Keenan Wynn, Bobby Van, James Whitmore, Kurt Kasznar and Tommy Rall.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The film also prominently promoted its use of stereophonic sound.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Several other features that helped put 3D back on the map that month were the John Wayne feature *Hondo* (distributed by Warner Bros.), Columbia's *Miss Sadie Thompson* with Rita Hayworth, and Paramount's *Money From Home* with Dean Martin and Jerry Lewis.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Paramount also released the cartoon shorts *Boo Moon* with Casper, the Friendly Ghost and *Popeye, Ace of Space* with Popeye the Sailor.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Paramount Pictures released a 3D Korean War film *Cease Fire* filmed on actual Korean locations in 1953.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] A string of successful films filmed in 3D followed the second wave, but many were widely or exclusively shown flat.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] 3D's final decline was in the late spring of 1954, for the same reasons as the previous lull, as well as the further success of widescreen formats with theater operators.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Even though Polaroid had created a well-designed "Tell-Tale Filter Kit" for the purpose of recognizing and adjusting out of sync and phase 3D, exhibitors still felt uncomfortable with the system and turned their focus instead to processes such as CinemaScope.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The last 3D feature to be released in that format during the "Golden era" was *Revenge of the Creature*, on February 23, 1955.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Ironically, the film had a wide release in 3D and was well received at the box office.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Stereoscopic films largely remained dormant for the first part of the 1960s, with those that were released usually being anaglyph exploitation films.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] One film of notoriety was the Beaver-Champion/Warner Bros. production, *The Mask* (1961).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The film was shot in 2-D, but to enhance the bizarre qualities of the dream-world that is induced when the main character puts on a cursed tribal mask, these scenes went to anaglyph 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] These scenes were printed by Technicolor on their first run in red/green anaglyph.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Although 3D films appeared sparsely during the early 1960s, the true second wave of 3D cinema was set into motion by Arch Oboler, the producer who had started the craze of the 1950s.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Using a new technology called *Space-Vision 3D*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The origin of "Space-Vision 3D" goes back to Colonel Robert Vincent Bernier, a forgotten innovator in the history of stereoscopic motion pictures.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] His Trioptiscope Space-Vision lens was the gold standard for the production and exhibition of 3-D films for nearly 30 years.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] "Space-Vision 3D" stereoscopic films were printed with two images, one above the other, in a single academy ratio frame, on a single strip, and needed only one projector fitted with a special lens.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] This so-called "over and under" technique eliminated the need for dual projector set-ups, and produced widescreen, but darker, less vivid, polarized 3D images.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Unlike earlier dual system, it could stay in perfect synchronization, unless improperly spliced in repair.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Arch Oboler once again had the vision for the system that no one else would touch, and put it to use on his film entitled *The Bubble*, which starred Michael Cole, Deborah Walley, and Johnny Desmond.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] As with *Bwana Devil*, the critics panned *The Bubble*, but audiences flocked to see it, and it became financially sound enough to promote the use of the system to other studios, particularly independents, who did not have the money for expensive dual-strip prints of their productions.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In 1970, Stereovision, a new entity founded by director/inventor Allan Silliphant and optical designer Chris Condon, developed a different 35 mm single-strip format, which printed two images squeezed side by side and used an anamorphic lens to widen the pictures through Polaroid filters.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Sher (Sherpix) and Stereovision released the softcore sex comedy *The Stewardesses* (self-rated X, but later re-rated R by the MPAA).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Some 36 films worldwide were made with Stereovision over 25 years, using either a widescreen (above-below), anamorphic (side by side) or 70 mm 3D formats.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In 2009 *The Stewardesses* was remastered by Chris Condon and director Ed Meyer, releasing it in XpanD 3D, RealD 3D and Dolby 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The quality of the 1970s 3D films was not much more inventive, as many were either softcore and even hardcore adult films, horror films, or a combination of both.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Paul Morrisey's *Flesh For Frankenstein* (aka *Andy Warhol's Frankenstein*) was a superlative example of such a combination.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Between 1981 and 1983 there was a new Hollywood 3D craze started by the spaghetti western *Comin' at Ya!*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] When *Parasite* was released it was billed as the first horror film to come out in 3D in over 20 years.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Horror films and reissues of 1950s 3D classics (such as Hitchcock's *Dial M for Murder*) dominated the 3D releases that followed.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The second sequel in the *Friday the 13th* series, *Friday the 13th Part III*, was released very successfully.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Apparently saying "part 3 in 3D" was considered too cumbersome so it was shortened in the titles of *Jaws 3-D* and *Amityville 3-D*, which emphasized the screen effects to the point of being annoying at times, especially when flashlights were shone into the eyes of the audience.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The science fiction film *Spacehunter: Adventures in the Forbidden Zone* was the most expensive 3D film made up to that point with production costs about the same as *Star Wars* but not nearly the same box office success, causing the craze to fade quickly through spring 1983.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Other sci-fi/fantasy films were released as well including *Metalstorm: The Destruction of Jared-Syn* and *Treasure of the Four Crowns*, which was widely criticized for poor editing and plot holes, but did feature some truly spectacular closeups.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] 3D releases after the second craze included *The Man Who Wasn't There* (1983), *Silent Madness* and the 1985 animated film *Starchaser: The Legend of Orin*, whose plot seemed to borrow heavily from *Star Wars*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Only *Comin' At Ya!*, *Parasite*, and *Friday the 13th Part III* have been officially released on VHS and/or DVD in 3D in the United States (although *Amityville 3D* has seen a 3D DVD release in the United Kingdom).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Most of the 1980s 3D films and some of the classic 1950s films such as *House of Wax* were released on the now defunct Video Disc (VHD) format in Japan as part of a system that used shutter glasses.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Most of these have been unofficially transferred to DVD and are available on the grey market through sites such as eBay.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Stereoscopic movies were also popular in other parts of the world, such as My Dear Kuttichathan, a Malayalam film which was shot with stereoscopic 3D and released in 1984.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In the mid-1980s, IMAX began producing non-fiction films for its nascent 3D business, starting with *We Are Born of Stars* (Roman Kroitor, 1985).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] A key point was that this production, as with all subsequent IMAX productions, emphasized mathematical correctness of the 3D rendition and thus largely eliminated the eye fatigue and pain that resulted from the approximate geometries of previous 3D incarnations.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In addition, and in contrast to previous 35mm-based 3D presentations, the very large field of view provided by IMAX allowed a much broader 3D "stage", arguably as important in 3D film as it is theatre.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The Walt Disney Company also began more prominent use of 3D films in special venues to impress audiences with Magic Journeys (1982) and *Captain EO* (Francis Ford Coppola, 1986, starring Michael Jackson) being notable examples.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In the same year, the National Film Board of Canada production *Transitions* (Colin Low), created for Expo 86 in Vancouver, was the first IMAX presentation using polarized glasses.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] *Echoes of the Sun* (Roman Kroitor, 1990) was the first IMAX film to be presented using alternate-eye shutterglass technology, a development required because the dome screen precluded the use of polarized technology.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] From 1990 onward, numerous films were produced by all three parties to satisfy the demands of their various high-profile special attractions and IMAX's expanding 3D network.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Films of special note during this period include the extremely successful *Into the Deep* (Graeme Ferguson, 1995) and the first IMAX 3D fiction film *Wings of Courage* (1996), by director Jean-Jacques Annaud, about the pilot Henri Guillaumet.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] By 2004, 54% of IMAX theaters (133 of 248) were capable of showing 3D films.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Shortly thereafter, higher quality computer animation, competition from DVDs and other media, digital projection, digital video capture, and the use of sophisticated IMAX 70mm film projectors, created an opportunity for another wave of 3D films.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In 2003, *Ghosts of the Abyss* by James Cameron was released as the first full-length 3D IMAX feature filmed with the Reality Camera System.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] This camera system used the latest HD video cameras, not film, and was built for Cameron by Vince Pace, to his specifications.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The same camera system was used to film *Spy Kids 3-D: Game Over* (2003), *Aliens of the Deep* IMAX (2005), and *The Adventures of Sharkboy and Lavagirl in 3-D* (2005).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In 2004, Las Vegas Hilton released Star Trek: The Experience which included two films.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] One of the films, *Borg Invasion 4-D* (Ty Granoroli), was in 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In August of the same year, rap group Insane Clown Posse released their ninth studio album *Hell's Pit*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] One of two versions of the album contained a DVD featuring a 3D short film for the track "Bowling Balls", shot in high-definition video.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In November 2004, *The Polar Express* was released as IMAX's first full-length, animated 3D feature.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] It was released in 3,584 theaters in 2D, and only 66 IMAX locations.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The return from those few 3D theaters was about 25% of the total.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The 3D version earned about 14 times as much per screen as the 2D version.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] This pattern continued and prompted a greatly intensified interest in 3D and 3D presentation of animated films.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In June 2005, the Mann's Chinese 6 theatre in Hollywood became the first commercial film theatre to be equipped with the Digital 3D format.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Both *Singin' in the Rain* and *The Polar Express* were tested in the Digital 3D format over the course of several months.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In November 2005, Walt Disney Pictures released *Chicken Little* in Digital 3D format.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Ben Walters suggested in 2009 that both filmmakers and film exhibitors regain interest in 3D film.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] There was more 3D exhibition equipment, and more dramatic films being shot in 3D format.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] One incentive is that the technology is more mature.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Shooting in 3D format is less limited, and the result is more stable.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Another incentive was the fact that while 2D ticket sales were in an overall state of decline, revenues from 3D tickets continued to grow at the time.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Through the entire history of 3D presentations, techniques to convert existing 2D images for 3D presentation have existed.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The combination of digital and digitized source material with relatively cost-effective digital post-processing has spawned a new wave of conversion products.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In June 2006, IMAX and Warner Bros. released *Superman Returns* including 20 minutes of 3D images converted from the 2D original digital footage.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] George Lucas announced that he would re-release his *Star Wars* films in 3D based on a conversion process from the company In-Three.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Later on in 2011, it was announced that Lucas was working with the company Prime Focus on this conversion.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In late 2005, Steven Spielberg told the press he was involved in patenting a 3D cinema system that did not need glasses, based on plasma screens.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] A computer splits each film-frame, and then projects the two split images onto the screen at differing angles, to be picked up by tiny angled ridges on the screen.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Animated films *Open Season*, and *The Ant Bully*, were released in analog 3D in 2006.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] *Monster House* and *The Nightmare Before Christmas* were released on XpanD 3D, RealD 3D and Dolby 3D systems in 2006.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] On May 19, 2007 *Scar3D* opened at the Cannes Film Market.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] It was the first US-produced 3D full-length feature film to be completed in RealD 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] It has been the #1 film at the box office in several countries around the world, including Russia where it opened in 3D on 295 screens.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] On January 19, 2008, U2 3D was released; it was the first live-action digital 3D film.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In the same year others 3D films included *Hannah Montana & Miley Cyrus: Best of Both Worlds Concert*, *Journey to the Center of the Earth*, and *Bolt*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] On January 16, 2009, Lionsgate released *My Bloody Valentine 3D*, the first horror film and first R-rated film to be projected in RealD 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] It was released to 1,033 3D screens, the most ever for this format, and 1,501 regular screens.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Another R-rated film, *The Final Destination*, was released later that year in August on even more screens.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] It was the first of its series to be released in HD 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Major 3D films in 2009 included *Coraline*, *Monsters vs.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Aliens*, *Up*, *X Games 3D: The Movie*, *The Final Destination*, *Disney's A Christmas Carol*, and *Avatar*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] *Avatar* has gone on to be one of the most expensive films of all time, with a budget at $237 million; it is also the highest-grossing film of all time.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The main technologies used to exhibit these films, and many others released around the time and up to the present, are RealD 3D, Dolby 3D, XpanD 3D, MasterImage 3D, and IMAX 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The success of the film also led to electronics manufacturers releasing 3D televisions and caused 3D films to increase in popularity.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] March and April 2010 saw three major 3D releases clustered together, with *Alice in Wonderland* hitting US theaters on March 5, 2010, *How to Train Your Dragon* on March 26, 2010, and *Clash of the Titans* on April 2, 2010.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] On May 13 of the same year, China's first IMAX 3D film started shooting.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The pre-production of the first 3D film shot in France, *Derrière les murs*, began in May 2010 and was released in mid-2011.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] On October 1, 2010 *Scar3D* was the first-ever stereoscopic 3D Video-on-demand film released through major cable broadcasters for 3D televisions in the United States.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Released in the United States on May 21, 2010, *Shrek Forever After* by DreamWorks Animation (Paramount Pictures) used the RealD 3D system, also released in IMAX 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In September 2003, Sabucat Productions organized the first World 3-D Exposition, celebrating the 50th anniversary of the original craze.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The Expo was held at Grauman's Egyptian Theatre.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In attendance were many stars from each film, respectively, and some were moved to tears by the sold-out seating with audiences of film buffs from all over the world who came to remember their previous glories.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In May 2006, the second World 3-D Exposition was announced for September of that year, presented by the 3-D Film Preservation Fund.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Along with the favorites of the previous exposition were newly discovered features and shorts, and like the previous Expo, guests from each film.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Expo II was announced as being the locale for the world premiere of several films never before seen in 3D, including *The Diamond Wizard* and the Universal short, *Hawaiian Nights* with Mamie Van Doren and Pinky Lee.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Other "re-premieres" of films not seen since their original release in stereoscopic form included *Cease Fire!*, *Taza, Son of Cochise*, *Wings of the Hawk*, and *Those Redheads From Seattle*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Also shown were the long-lost shorts *Carmenesque* and *A Day in the Country* (both 1953) and William Van Doren Kelley's two *Plasticon* shorts (1922 and 1923).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In the wake of its initial popularity and corresponding increase in the number of screens, more films were being released in the 3D format, yet fewer people were choosing to see them in such a way.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] For instance, only 45% of the premiere weekend box office earnings of *Kung Fu Panda 2* in 2011 came from 3D screenings as opposed to 60% for *Shrek Forever After* in 2010.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In addition, the premiere of *Cars 2* opening weekend gross consisted of only 37% from 3D theatres.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] *Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows – Part 2* and *Captain America: The First Avenger* were major releases that achieved similar percentages: 43% and 40% respectively.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In view of this trend, there has been box office analysis concluding the implementation of 3D presentation is apparently backfiring by discouraging people from going to film theatres at all.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] As Brandon Gray of Box Office Mojo notes, "In each case, 3D's more-money-from-fewer-people approach has simply led to less money from even fewer people." Parallel, the number of televisions sold with support for 3D television has dropped, let alone those sold with actual 3D goggles.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] According to the Motion Picture Association of America, despite a record total of 47 3D films being released in 2011, the overall domestic box office receipts were down 18% to $1.8 billion from $2.2 billion in 2010.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Although revenues as a whole increased during 2012, the bulk has so far come from 2D presentations as exemplified by little over 50% of filmgoers opting to see the likes of *The Avengers* and 32% choosing *Brave* in their 3D versions.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Conflicting reasons are respectively offered by studios and exhibitors: whereas the former blame more expensive 3D ticket prices, the latter argue that the quality of films in general is at fault.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] However, despite the perceived decline of 3D in the U.S. market, studio chiefs in 2012 were optimistic of better receipts internationally, where there still appeared to be a strong appetite for the format.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Studios are also using 3D to generate additional income from films that are already commercially successful.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Such re-releases usually involve a conversion from 2D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] For example, Disney has reissued both *The Lion King* and *Beauty and the Beast*, with plans to add some of its other well-known titles.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] *Titanic* has also been modified for 3D, and there are also plans to similarly present all six *Star Wars* films.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Jeffrey Katzenberg, a producer of 3D films and one of the leading proponents of the format, blames oversaturation of the market with inferior films, especially ones photographed conventionally and then digitally processed in post-production.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] He claims that such films have led audiences to conclude that the format is not worth the often much higher ticket price.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Daniel Engber, a columnist for *Slate*, comes to a similar conclusion: "What happened to 3-D?
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Film critic Mark Kermode, a noted detractor of 3D, has surmised that there is an emerging policy of distributors to limit the availability of 2D versions, thus "railroading" the 3D format into cinemas whether the paying filmgoer likes it or not.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] This was especially prevalent during the release of *Prometheus* in 2012, where only 30% of prints for theatrical exhibition (at least in the UK) were in 2D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] His suspicions were later reinforced by a substantial number of complaints about *Dredd* from those who wished to see it in 2D but were denied the opportunity.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In July 2017, IMAX announced that they would begin to focus on screening more Hollywood tentpole movies in 2D (even if there's a 3D version) and have fewer 3D screenings of movies in North America, citing that moviegoers in North America prefer 2D films over 3D films.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In 2024, 3D films in 4K HDR became available to home media for the first time, with the launch of the visionOS operating system offering two services to access movies in such formats: Apple TV and Disney+.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Some films were also offered in high frame rate (48fps), such as *Avatar: The Way of Water*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In 2025, 3D films became available to Android XR devices via the Google TV service, starting with the Samsung Galaxy XR.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Stereoscopic motion pictures can be produced through a variety of different methods.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Over the years the popularity of systems being widely employed in film theaters has waxed and waned.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Though anaglyph was sometimes used prior to 1948, during the early "Golden Era" of 3D cinematography of the 1950s the polarization system was used for every single feature-length film in the United States, and all but one short film.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In the 21st century, polarization 3D systems have continued to dominate the scene, though during the 1960s and 1970s some classic films which were converted to anaglyph for theaters not equipped for polarization, and were even shown in 3D on television.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In the years following the mid-1980s, some films were made with short segments in anaglyph 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The following are some of the technical details and methodologies employed in some of the more notable 3D film systems that have been developed.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The standard for shooting live-action films in 3D involves using two cameras mounted so that their lenses are about as far apart from each other as the average pair of human eyes, recording two separate images for both the left eye and the right eye.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In principle, two normal 2D cameras could be put side-to-side but this is problematic in many ways.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The only real option is to invest in new stereoscopic cameras.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Moreover, some cinematographic tricks that are simple with a 2D camera become impossible when filming in 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] This means those otherwise cheap tricks need to be replaced by expensive CGI.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In 2008, *Journey to the Center of the Earth* became the first live-action feature film to be shot with the earliest Fusion Camera System released in Digital 3D and was later followed by several others.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] *Avatar* (2009) was shot in a 3D process that is based on how the human eye looks at an image.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] It was an improvement to the existing 3D camera system.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Many 3D camera rigs still in use simply pair two cameras side by side, while newer rigs are paired with a beam splitter or both camera lenses built into one unit.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] While Digital Cinema cameras are not a requirement for 3D they are the predominant medium for most of what is photographed.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Film options include IMAX 3D and Cine 160.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In the 1930s and 1940s, the Fleischer Studios made several cartoons with extensive stereoscopic 3D backgrounds, including several *Popeye the Sailor*, *Betty Boop*, and *Superman* cartoons.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In the early to mid-1950s, only half of the major Animation film studios operation experimented with creating traditional 3D animated short subjects.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The Walt Disney Studio produced two traditionally animated shorts in stereoscopic 3D, for cinemas.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] *Adventures in Music: Melody* (1953), and the Donald Duck cartoon *Working for Peanuts* (1953).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Cartoons only produced a single cartoon in 3D: *Lumber Jack-Rabbit* (1953) starring Bugs Bunny.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Famous Studios produced two cartoons in 3D, the Popeye cartoon *Popeye, the Ace of Space* (1953), and the Casper the Friendly Ghost cartoon *Boo Moon* (1954).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Walter Lantz Productions produced the Woody Woodpecker cartoon *Hypnotic Hick* (1953), which was distributed by Universal.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] From the late 1950s until the mid-2000s almost no animation was produced for 3D display in theaters.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Although several films used 3D backgrounds.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] One exception is *Starchaser: The Legend of Orin*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] CGI animated films can be rendered as stereoscopic 3D version by using two virtual cameras.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Stop-motion animated 3D films are photographed with two cameras similar to live action 3D films.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In 2004 *The Polar Express* was the first stereoscopic 3D CGI-animated feature film.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The 3D version was solely released in IMAX theaters.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In November 2005, Walt Disney Pictures released *Chicken Little* in Digital 3D format, being Disney's first CGI-animated film in 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The film was converted from 2D into 3D in post-production. nWave Pictures' *Fly Me to the Moon* (2008) was actually the first animated film created for 3D and released exclusively in 3D in digital theaters around the world.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] No other animation films have released solely in 3D since.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The first 3D feature by DreamWorks Animation, *Monsters vs.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Aliens*, followed in 2009 and used a new digital rendering process called InTru3D, which was developed by Intel to create more realistic animated 3D images.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] InTru3D is not used to exhibit 3D films in theaters; they are shown in either RealD 3D or IMAX 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In the case of 2D CGI animated films that were generated from 3D models, it is possible to return to the models to generate a 3D version.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] For all other 2D films, different techniques must be employed.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] For example, for the 3D re-release of the 1993 film *The Nightmare Before Christmas*, Walt Disney Pictures scanned each original frame and manipulated them to produce left-eye and right-eye versions.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Dozens of films have now been converted from 2D to 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] There are several approaches used for 2D to 3D conversion, most notably depth-based methods.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Information is unavailable as 2D does not have information for a perspective view.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Some TVs have a 3D engine to convert 2D content to 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Usually, on high frame rate content (and on some slower processors even normal frame rate) the processor is not fast enough and lag is possible.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] This can lead to strange visual effects.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Anaglyph images were the earliest method of presenting theatrical 3D, and the one most commonly associated with stereoscopy by the public at large, mostly because of non-theatrical 3D media such as comic books and 3D television broadcasts, where polarization is not practical.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] They were made popular because of the ease of their production and exhibition.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The first anaglyph film was invented in 1915 by Edwin S Porter.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Though the earliest theatrical presentations were done with this system, most 3D films from the 1950s and 1980s were originally shown polarized.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In an anaglyph, the two images are superimposed in an additive light setting through two filters, one red and one cyan.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In a subtractive light setting, the two images are printed in the same complementary colors on white paper.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Glasses with colored filters in each eye separate the appropriate images by canceling the filter color out and rendering the complementary color black.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Anaglyph images are much easier to view than either parallel sighting or crossed eye stereograms, although the latter types offer bright and accurate color rendering, particularly in the red component, which is muted, or desaturated with even the best color anaglyphs.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] A compensating technique, commonly known as Anachrome, uses a slightly more transparent cyan filter in the patented glasses associated with the technique.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Process reconfigures the typical anaglyph image to have less parallax.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] An alternative to the usual red and cyan filter system of anaglyph is ColorCode 3-D, a patented anaglyph system which was invented in order to present an anaglyph image in conjunction with the NTSC television standard, in which the red channel is often compromised.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] ColorCode uses the complementary colors of yellow and dark blue on-screen, and the colors of the glasses' lenses are amber and dark blue.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The polarization 3D system has been the standard for theatrical presentations since it was used for *Bwana Devil* in 1952, though early IMAX presentations were done using the eclipse system and in the 1960s and 1970s classic 3D films were sometimes converted to anaglyph for special presentations.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The polarization system has better color fidelity and less ghosting than the anaglyph system.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In the post-'50s era, anaglyph has been used instead of polarization in feature presentations where only part of the film is in 3D such as in the 3D segment of *Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare* and the 3D segments of *Spy Kids 3-D: Game Over*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Anaglyph is also used in printed materials and in 3D television broadcasts where polarization is not practical.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] 3D polarized televisions and other displays only became available from several manufacturers in 2008; these generate polarization on the receiving end.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] To present a stereoscopic motion pictures, two images are projected superimposed onto the same screen through different polarizing filters.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The viewer wears low-cost glasses which also contain a pair of polarizing filters oriented differently (clockwise/counterclockwise with circular polarization or at 90 degree angles, usually 45 and 135 degrees, with linear polarization).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] As each filter passes only that light which is similarly polarized and blocks the light polarized differently, each eye sees a different image.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] This is used to produce a three-dimensional effect by projecting the same scene into both eyes, but depicted from slightly different perspectives.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Since no head tracking is involved, the entire audience can view the stereoscopic images at the same time.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Circular polarization has an advantage over linear polarization, in that the viewer does not need to have their head upright and aligned with the screen for the polarization to work properly.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] With linear polarization, turning the glasses sideways causes the filters to go out of alignment with the screen filters causing the image to fade and for each eye to see the opposite frame more easily.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] For circular polarization, the polarizing effect works regardless of how the viewer's head is aligned with the screen such as tilted sideways, or even upside down.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The left eye will still only see the image intended for it, and vice versa, without fading or crosstalk.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Nonetheless, 3D cinema films are made to be viewed without head tilt, and any significant head tilt will result in incorrect parallax and prevent binocular fusion.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In the case of RealD a circularly polarizing liquid crystal filter which can switch polarity 144 times per second is placed in front of the projector lens.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Only one projector is needed, as the left and right eye images are displayed alternately.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Sony features a new system called RealD XLS, which shows both circular polarized images simultaneously: A single 4K projector (4096×2160 resolution) displays both 2K images (2048×1080 resolution) on top of each other at the same time, a special lens attachment polarizes and projects the images.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Optical attachments can be added to traditional 35 mm projectors to adapt them for projecting film in the "over-and-under" format, in which each pair of images is stacked within one frame of film.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The two images are projected through different polarizers and superimposed on the screen.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] This is a very cost-effective way to convert a theater for 3D as all that is needed are the attachments and a non-depolarizing screen surface, rather than a conversion to digital 3D projection.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Thomson Technicolor currently produces an adapter of this type.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] A metallic screen is necessary for these systems as reflection from non-metallic surfaces destroys the polarization of the light.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Polarized stereoscopic pictures have been around since 1936, when Edwin H.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Land first applied it to motion pictures.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The so-called "3-D movie craze" in the years 1952 through 1955 was almost entirely offered in theaters using linear polarizing projection and glasses.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Only a minute amount of the total 3D films shown in the period used the anaglyph color filter method.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Linear polarization was likewise used with consumer level stereo projectors.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Polarization was also used during the 3D revival of the 1980s.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In the 2000s, computer animation, competition from DVDs and other media, digital projection, and the use of sophisticated IMAX 70 mm film projectors, have created an opportunity for a new wave of polarized 3D films.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] All types of polarization will result in a darkening of the displayed image and poorer contrast compared to non-3D images.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Light from lamps is normally emitted as a random collection of polarizations, while a polarization filter only passes a fraction of the light.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] As a result, the screen image is darker.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] This darkening can be compensated by increasing the brightness of the projector light source.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] If the initial polarization filter is inserted between the lamp and the image generation element, the light intensity striking the image element is not any higher than normal without the polarizing filter, and overall image contrast transmitted to the screen is not affected.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In this technology, a mechanism is used to block light from each appropriate eye when the converse eye's image is projected on the screen.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The technology originated with the Eclipse Method, in which the projector alternates between left and right images, and opens and closes the shutters in the glasses or viewer in synchronization with the images on the screen.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] This was the basis of the Teleview system which was used briefly in 1922.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] A newer implementation of the Eclipse Method came with liquid-crystal shutter glasses.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Glasses containing liquid crystal that will let light through in synchronization with the images on the cinema, television or computer screen, using the concept of alternate-frame sequencing.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] This is the method used by nVidia, XpanD 3D, and earlier IMAX systems.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] A drawback of this method is the need for each person viewing to wear expensive, electronic glasses that must be synchronized with the display system using a wireless signal or attached wire.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The shutter-glasses are heavier than most polarized glasses, though lighter models are no heavier than some sunglasses or deluxe polarized glasses.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] However these systems do not require a silver screen for projected images.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Liquid crystal light valves work by rotating light between two polarizing filters.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Due to these internal polarizers, LCD shutter-glasses darken the display image of any LCD, plasma, or projector image source, which has the result that images appear dimmer and contrast is lower than for normal non-3D viewing.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] This is not necessarily a usage problem; for some types of displays which are already very bright with poor grayish black levels, LCD shutter glasses may actually improve the image quality.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Dolby 3D uses specific wavelengths of red, green, and blue for the right eye, and different wavelengths of red, green, and blue for the left eye.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Glasses which filter out the very specific wavelengths allow the wearer to see a 3D image.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] This technology eliminates the expensive silver screens required for polarized systems such as RealD, which is the most common 3D display system in theaters.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] It does, however, require much more expensive glasses than the polarized systems.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The recently introduced Omega 3D/Panavision 3D system also uses this technology, though with a wider spectrum and more "teeth" to the "comb" (5 for each eye in the Omega/Panavision system).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The use of more spectral bands per eye eliminates the need to color process the image, required by the Dolby system.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Evenly dividing the visible spectrum between the eyes gives the viewer a more relaxed "feel" as the light energy and color balance is nearly 50-50.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Like the Dolby system, the Omega system can be used with white or silver screens.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] But it can be used with either film or digital projectors, unlike the Dolby filters that are only used on a digital system with a color correcting processor provided by Dolby.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The Omega/Panavision system also claims that their glasses are cheaper to manufacture than those used by Dolby.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In June 2012 the Omega 3D/Panavision 3D system was discontinued by DPVO Theatrical, who marketed it on behalf of Panavision, citing "challenging global economic and 3D market conditions".
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Although DPVO dissolved its business operations, Omega Optical continues promoting and selling 3D systems to non-theatrical markets.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Omega Optical's 3D system contains projection filters and 3D glasses.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In addition to the passive stereoscopic 3D system, Omega Optical has produced enhanced anaglyph 3D glasses.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The Omega's red/cyan anaglyph glasses use complex metal oxide thin film coatings and high quality annealed glass optics.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In this method, glasses are not necessary to see a 3D image.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] To produce the 3D effect, the person must be positioned so that one eye sees one of the two images and the other sees the other.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Both images are projected onto a high-gain, corrugated screen that reflects light at acute angles.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] In order to see the stereoscopic image, the viewer must sit within a very narrow angle that is nearly perpendicular to the screen, limiting the size of the audience.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Lenticular was used for theatrical presentation of numerous shorts in Russia from 1940 to 1948 and in 1946 for the feature-length film Robinson Crusoe.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Though lenticular's use in theatrical presentations has been rather limited, it has been widely used for a variety of novelty items and has even been used in amateur 3D photography.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Recent use includes the Fujifilm FinePix Real 3D with an autostereoscopic display that was released in 2009.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Other examples for this technology include autostereoscopic liquid crystal displays on monitors, notebooks, TVs, mobile phones and gaming devices, such as the Nintendo 3DS.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Some viewers have complained of headaches and eyestrain after watching 3D films.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Motion sickness, in addition to other health concerns, are more easily induced by 3D presentations.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] One published study shows that of those who watch 3D films, nearly 55% experience varying levels of headaches, nausea and disorientation.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] Glasses designed to eliminate eyestrain by converting 3D images back into 2D have been developed.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] It is believed that approximately 12% of people are unable to properly see 3D images, due to a variety of medical conditions.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] According to another experiment up to 30% of people have very weak stereoscopic vision preventing them from depth perception based on stereo disparity.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] This nullifies or greatly decreases immersion effects of digital stereo to them.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p02] The French National Research Agency (ANR) has sponsored multidisciplinary research in order to understand the effects of 3D film viewing, its grammar, and its acceptance.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] Most of the cues required to provide humans with relative depth information are already present in traditional 2D films.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] In fact, only two of these depth cues are not already present in 2D films: stereopsis (or parallax) and the focus of the eyeball (accommodation).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] 3D film-making addresses accurate presentation of stereopsis but not of accommodation, and therefore is insufficient in providing a complete 3D illusion.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] However, promising results from research aimed at overcoming this shortcoming were presented at the 2010 Stereoscopic Displays and Applications conference in San Jose, U.S.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] Film critic Mark Kermode argued that 3D adds "not that much" value to a film, and said that, while he liked *Avatar*, the many impressive things he saw in the film had nothing to do with 3D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] Kermode has been an outspoken critic of 3D film describing the effect as a "nonsense" and recommends using two right or left lenses from the 3D glasses to cut out the "pointy, pointy 3D stereoscopic vision", although this technique still does not improve the huge brightness loss from a 3D film.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] Versions of these "2-D glasses" are being marketed.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] Director Christopher Nolan has criticised the notion that traditional film does not allow depth perception, saying "I think it's a misnomer to call it 3D versus 2D.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] The whole point of cinematic imagery is it's three dimensional...
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] Late film critic Roger Ebert repeatedly criticized 3D film as being "too dim", sometimes distracting or even nausea-inducing, and argued that it is an expensive technology that adds nothing of value to the film-going experience (since 2-D films already provide a sufficient illusion of 3D).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] While Ebert was "not opposed to 3-D as an option", he opposed it as a replacement for traditional film, and preferred 2-D technologies such as MaxiVision48 that improve image area/resolution and frames per second.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] Most 3D systems will cut down the brightness of the picture considerably – the light loss can be as high as 88%.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] Some of this loss may be compensated by running the projector's bulb at higher power or using more powerful bulbs.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] The 2D brightness cinema standard is 14 foot-lamberts (48 candela per square metre), as set by the SMPTE standard 196M.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] As of 2012, there is no official standard for 3D brightness.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] According to the industry de facto standard, however, the "acceptable brightness range" goes as low as 3.5 fL (12 cd/m2) – just 25% of the standard 2D brightness.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] In September 2012, the DCI standards body issued a "recommended practice" calling for a 3D projection brightness of 7 fL (24 cd/m2), with an acceptable range of 5–9 fL (17–31 cd/m2).
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] It is not known how many theaters actually achieve such light levels with current technology.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] Prototype laser projection systems have reached 14 fL (48 cd/m2) for 3D on a cinema screen.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] Another major criticism is that many of the films in the 21st century to date were not filmed in 3D, but converted to 3D after filming.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] Filmmakers who have criticized the quality of this process include James Cameron (whose film *Avatar* was created mostly in 3D from the ground up, with some portions of the film created in 2D, and is largely credited with the revival of 3D) and Michael Bay.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] However, Cameron has said that quality 2D to 3D conversions can be done if they take the time they need and the director is involved.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] Cameron's *Titanic* was converted into 3D in 2012, taking 60 weeks and costing $18 million.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] In contrast, computer-animated films for which the original computer models are still available can be rendered in 3D easily, as the depth information is still available and does not need to be inferred or approximated.
[src:serial-digital-interface/3d-video-p03] This has been done with *Toy Story*, among others.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The **405-line** monochrome analogue television broadcasting system was the first fully electronic television system to be used in regular broadcasting.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The number of television lines influences the image resolution, or quality of the picture.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] It was introduced with the BBC Television Service in 1936, suspended for the duration of World War II, and remained in operation in the UK until 1985.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] It was also used between 1961 and 1982 in Ireland, as well as from 1957 to 1973 for the Rediffusion Television cable service in Hong Kong.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] 405-line was approved as **System A** in the CCIR assignment of broadcast systems.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Sometimes called the **Marconi-EMI system**, it was developed in 1934 by the EMI Research Team led by Isaac Shoenberg.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The figure of 405 lines had been chosen following discussions over Sunday lunch at the home of Alan Blumlein.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The system used interlacing; EMI had been experimenting with a 243-line all-electronic interlaced system since 1933.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] In the 405 system the scanning lines were broadcast in two complementary fields, 50 times per second, creating 25 frames per second.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The actual image was 376 lines high and interlaced, with additional unused lines making the frame up to 405 lines to give the slow circuitry time to prepare for the next frame; in modern terms it would be described as *"376i"*.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] At the time of its introduction the 405-line system was referred to as *"high definition"* – which it was, compared to earlier systems, although of lower definition than 625-line and later standards.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] In the United States, the FCC had briefly approved a 405-line color television standard in October 1950, which was developed by CBS.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The CBS system was incompatible with existing black-and-white receivers.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] It used a rotating color wheel, reduced the number of scan lines from 525 to 405, and increased the field rate from 60 to 144, but had an effective frame rate of only 24 frames per second.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] In 1934, the British government set up a committee (the "Television Committee") to advise on the future of TV broadcasting.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The committee recommended that a "high definition" service (defined by them as being a system of 240 lines or more) should be run and established by the BBC.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The recommendation was accepted and tenders were sought from industry.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Two tenders were received: one from the Baird company offering a 240-line mechanical system, and the other from EMI offering a 405-line all-electronic one.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The Television Committee advised that they were unable to choose between the two systems and that both tenders should be accepted, the two systems to be run together for an experimental period.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] This became the standard for all British TV broadcasts until the 1960s.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] It soon became apparent that television reception was also possible well outside the original intended service area.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] In February 1938, engineers at the RCA Research Station, Riverhead, Long Island, New York, in the US, were able to receive the BBC signal 5,000 km (3,100 mi) away, due to the signal being "bounced" back to earth from the ionosphere.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] A few minutes of programming were recorded on 16mm movie film.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] This is now considered to be the only surviving example of pre-war live British television.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The images recorded included two of the original three BBC announcers, Jasmine Bligh and (in a brief shot) Elizabeth Cowell, an excerpt from an unknown period costume drama, and the BBC's station identification transmitted at the beginning and end of the day's programmes.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The BBC temporarily ceased transmissions on 1 September 1939, the day of the German invasion of Poland, for the outbreak of World War II was imminent.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] After the BBC Television Service recommenced in 1946, distant reception reports were received from various parts of the world, including Italy, South Africa, India, the Middle East, North America and the Caribbean.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The BBC lost its monopoly of the British television market in 1954, and the following year the commercial network ITV, comprising a consortium of regional companies, was launched.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The subcarrier frequency was 2.6578125 MHz (525/2 times line frequency) with an "I" signal bandwidth of 500 kHz and a "Q" signal bandwidth of 300 kHz.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Tests with PAL, SECAM and other NTSC subcarrier frequencies were also attempted.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Some of these broadcasts were on UHF (also an experimental technology at the time), while others were carried over the regular VHF network outside of normal broadcasting hours.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] In 1964, the BBC launched its BBC2 service on UHF using only a 625-line system, which older sets could not receive.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] For several years BBC1 and ITV transmitted using the 405-line and BBC2 with the 625-line standard; the only way to receive them all was to use a complex "dual-standard" 405- and 625-line, VHF and UHF, receiver.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The introduction of colour on BBC2 in 1967 necessitated an even more complex dual-standard set to receive all three channels with BBC2 in colour.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Over time in 1968 and 1969, the different ITV regional channels and BBC1 switched over to broadcasting on the 625-line as well as the 405-line, a process which once completed meant that only 625-lines were necessary to receive all channels, with dual standard receivers no longer necessary.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] In November 1969, BBC1 and ITV started broadcasting in 625-line PAL colour on UHF.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Their programming was now entirely produced using the new 625-line standard, and thus the 405-line broadcasts served only as a rebroadcast in monochrome for people who did not have the newer receivers and who could only receive BBC1 and ITV.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] This situation continued up to 3–4 January 1985, with 405-line VHF receivers only being able to pick up BBC1 and ITV regionals, and in monochrome only, while 625-line UHF receivers could also receive BBC2 and Channel 4/S4C in addition to BBC1 and ITV, and in either colour or monochrome.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] One reason for the long switchover period was the difficulty in matching the coverage level of the new UHF 625-line service with the very high level of geographic coverage achieved with the 405-line VHF service.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The last 405-line transmissions were seen on 4 January 1985 in Scotland; they had been officially shut down one day earlier in the rest of the UK (although they were actually switched off at various points the next day).
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] This left only the UHF PAL system in operation in the UK.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The frequencies used by the 405-line system were initially left empty, but were later sold off; they are now used for other purposes, including DAB and trunked PMR commercial two-way radio systems.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Ireland's use of the 405-line system began in 1961 (officially 31st of December 1961), with the launch of Telefís Éireann, but only extended to two main transmitters and their five relays, serving the east and north of the country.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] This was because many people in these areas already had 405-line sets for receiving UK broadcasts from Wales or Northern Ireland.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Telefís Éireann's primary standard was 625-line; it began using this in the summer of 1962, more than two years before the UK had any 625-line channels.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The last 405 line transmitters in the UK and Ireland were shut down in 1985.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The last 405-line relays, in County Donegal, were turned off in 1982; the main transmitters had been shut down in 1978 to free up frequencies for RTÉ 2, and after then the relays had been fed by standards converters from the local 625-line transmitter.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] For the last five years of RTÉ's 405-line simulcasting, a simple orthicon converter was used, essentially a 405-line camera pointed at a 625-line monitor, as the more expensive system converters that RTÉ had previously used were now inoperable.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The 405-line system was used in the Rediffusion Television cable television service in Hong Kong, established in 1957, making it both the first British colony and the first predominantly Chinese city to have television.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The service of 405-line system ended in 1973, replaced by 625-line PAL system free-to-air broadcast.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] For a brief time in 1939 there were experimental 405-line transmissions from stations in Montrouge in France and Eindhoven in the Netherlands, Czechoslovakia and Switzerland.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] After the U.S. adopted the NTSC 525-line monochrome standard for commercial broadcasting in 1941, subsequent efforts were made to upgrade the standard so that it could also accommodate a "compatible" colour broadcasting system.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] This system was a field-sequential colour system which electronically transmitted a 405 lines, 144 fields per second monochrome picture.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Colour was provided mechanically by means of a synchronized rotating transparent Red-Green-Blue disk, which was placed in front of the receiver screen.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Regular broadcast channels were used to transmit the 405-line system signals, but the millions of existing NTSC 525-line television receivers could only correctly process the audio portion of these transmissions, so unless these sets were modified they would only display a jumbled picture.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] CBS aired a variety show special entitled *Premiere* on 25 June 1951 to officially launch commercial 405-line colour broadcasting, but just four months later CBS ended its colour broadcasts.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] CBS's efforts were hindered from the beginning by a widespread lack of acceptance, and the ultimate setback came at the end of the year when the U.S. government temporarily banned the manufacture of colour televisions, ostensibly to conserve resources during the Korean War.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] In 1953, the FCC rescinded its approval of the CBS 405-line colour system.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] In its place it approved a newly improved and now satisfactory second NTSC 525-line standard which had been developed by RCA.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] It provided for colour broadcasting yet remained compatible with existing 525-line monochrome sets.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] 405-line is System A in the CCIR assignment of broadcast systems.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The audio uses amplitude modulation rather than the frequency modulation in use on modern analogue systems.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] In addition, the system was broadcast in an aspect ratio of 5:4 until 3 April 1950, when it changed to the more common 4:3 format.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] All System A transmitters used vestigial sideband transmission, with the single exception of Alexandra Palace in London, which closed down in 1957 when it was replaced by Crystal Palace.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Secondly, the smoothing (filtering) of power supply circuits in early TV receivers was rather poor, and ripple superimposed on the DC could cause visual interference.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] However, the main problem was the susceptibility of the electron beam in the CRT being deflected by stray magnetic fields from nearby transformers or motors.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] If the picture was locked to the mains frequency, this interference would at least be static on the screen and thus relatively unnoticeable.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The very earliest TV sets used a mains transformer; care had to be taken in design to prevent the transformer's stray magnetic field from disturbing the electron beam in the CRT.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] An interlaced system requires accurate positioning of scanning lines so the horizontal and vertical timebase must be in a precise ratio.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] This is done by passing the one through a series of electronic divider circuits to produce the other.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Therefore, there has to be a straightforward mathematical relationship between the line and field frequencies, the latter being derived by dividing down from the former.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The technology constraints of the 1930s meant that this division process could only be done using small integers, preferably no greater than 7, for good stability.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The number of lines was odd because of 2:1 interlace.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The 405-line system used a vertical frequency of 50 Hz (standard AC mains supply frequency in Britain) and a horizontal one of 10,125 Hz (50 × 405 ÷ 2 or, using the frame rate, 25 x 405), with 405 being derived from (3 × 3 × 3 × 3 × 5).
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] A few 405-line videotapes still survive.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] However, the majority of surviving 405-line programmes are in the form of black and white film telerecordings, usually with optical soundtracks.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Occasionally video re-recording would be employed instead, with a 625-line camera pointing at a 405-line monitor.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] This preserves the original 50-field interlaced format, but with some geometrical distortions owing to the curvature of the CRT monitors used at the time.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] 405-line programming may be recorded and played on an unmodified VHS or Betamax video recorder, as long as the input to the recorder is baseband rather than RF.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Thus, various modern video recordings of 405-line programming also exist.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Betamax was sometimes preferred for this, as the dropout compensator could be switched off on certain models for use with PCM digital audio decoders.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] When used with vestigial sideband filtering, the total bandwidth of a 405-line TV channel is 5 MHz, significantly less than the 8 MHz required by the 625-line System I, which replaced it in Britain.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Systems in other countries used anything between six and fourteen megahertz of bandwidth per channel.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The use of VHF frequencies combined with the narrow vision bandwidth — AM signals (at VHF low band frequencies) are less affected by noise as bandwidth is reduced — meant that 405-line signals could be received well even under marginal conditions.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Therefore, it was possible to cover virtually all of the UK with a relatively small number of transmitting stations.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The use of AM (rather than FM) for sound and the use of positive (rather than negative) video modulation made 405-line signals very prone to audible and visible impulse interference, such as that generated by the ignition systems of vehicles.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Such interference manifested itself as a loud popping on sound and large bright spots on the picture, which viewers found much more noticeable than the dark spots encountered when such interference is encountered on a signal using negative video modulation.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] With positive modulation, interference could easily be of similar amplitude to the sync pulses (which were represented by 0–30% of the transmitter output).
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The early time-base circuits were less able to discriminate between the signals and the picture would break up.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] By contrast, in negative modulation sync, pulses represent peak transmitter output (70–100% output).
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] As a result, impulse interference would cause visual dark spots before it was large enough to affect the synchronisation of the picture.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] If the interference was large enough, the picture was probably unwatchable anyway.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The later introduction of flywheel sync circuits rendered the picture much more stable, but these could not have alleviated some of the problems with positive modulation.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Almost all television systems that succeeded the 405-line system adopted negative modulation for this reason alone.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] First-generation AGC merely detected the average value of the transmitted signal; however, due to the positively modulated carrier, peak power represented peak white – not guaranteed to be present.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Thus for a completely black picture, the AGC circuit would increase the RF gain to restore the average carrier amplitude.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The result was a screen that was not black but mid-grey.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] In fact, the total light output of early TV sets was practically constant regardless of the picture content.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] By the mid-1950s, several manufacturers started to introduce gated-AGC systems to avoid this issue.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] A delayed pulse was derived from the recovered line-sync signal.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] This pulse would trigger a gate which would sample the received video signal during the "back porch" which was a guaranteed black-level transmitted between the end of the line-sync pulse and the start of the picture information.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The introduction of negative modulation in later systems simplified the problem because peak carrier power represented sync pulses (which were always guaranteed to be present).
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] A simple peak-detector AGC circuit would detect the amplitude of only the sync pulses, thus measuring the strength of the received signal.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The 405-line system produced a noticeable 10.125 kHz whistle in many sets, equal to the number of lines per second.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] This high-pitched whistle was caused by magnetostriction in the line output transformer.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] This is a common artifact in sets that use a cathode-ray tube.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] While all CRT-based television systems produce such a noise, the higher number of lines per second in later standards produces frequencies (PAL's 15.625 kHz and NTSC's 15.734 kHz) that are at the upper end of the audible spectrum, which not all people are able to hear.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Modern sets using plasma, LCD or OLED display technology are completely free of this effect as they are composed of a million or more individually controllable elements, rather than using a single magnetically deflected beam, so there is no requirement to generate the scanning signal.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The question was raised again from time to time, but a series of tests, conducted during 1952 in cooperation with the British Radio Equipment Manufacturers' Association, confirmed that there was no general need for equalizing pulses.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] On some larger TV screen sizes, the scanned lines were not fat enough to give 100% coverage of the CRT.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] The result was a lined picture with darkness between each horizontal scanned line, reducing picture brightness and contrast.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Larger screen sets often used a spot wobble oscillator, that slightly elongated the scanning spot vertically at high frequency to avoid this line separation effect without reducing horizontal sharpness.
[src:serial-digital-interface/405-line-television-system] Spot wobble was also utilised when making telerecordings of 405-line programmes.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] The system's line frequency was 11.025 kHz and the broadcast frequencies were 46.0 MHz for vision and 43.2 MHz for sound, using a 4 MHz channel bandwidth.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Its image aspect ratio was close to 1.15:1.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] A project began in 1938 involving the National Post and several companies including Bosch, Blaupunkt, Loewe, Lorenz, TeKaDe and Telefunken that aimed to produce 10,000 receivers for the television system.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Telefunken marketed the *FE V,* announced in 1936, with a 26 x 21 cm screen and a tuning range of 38-60 MHz.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] The next year, 1937, the *Heimprojektions-FSE* was introduced, with a larger 50 x 40 cm screen, along with the *FE VI* with a 26 x 21 cm screen.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] In 1938, the *Tischfernseher TF 1* was released, with a 20 x 17 cm screen and a tuning range of 40-55 MHz.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] In 1937, Loewe created the *FE-D*, with a 24x20 cm screen and a tuning range of 35-55 MHz.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] In 1938, TeKaDe created a single model, the *FS38*, with a 30 x 27 cm screen and a tuning range of 43-52 MHz.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] A single-channel TV receiver, the *Einheitsempfänger E1* was created in 1939.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] It had a 29 cm (diagonal) screen, and consumed 185 watts when receiving television signals and 60 watts when receiving audio only.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Only a few units were built before the outbreak of World War II.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Due to the onset of World War II, only about 50 devices were installed in military hospitals and various government departments.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] The transmitter's aerials in Berlin were destroyed during an Allied Forces' bombing in November 1943, but the station was also relayed by a special coaxial cable network to "wide screen" public "TV-rooms" (*Fernsehstuben*) so it carried on this way until 1944.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Television programs were mainly for wounded soldiers of the Wehrmacht occupation troops who recovered in the Greater Paris Area hospitals, but they also included French-language shows.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Broadcasts were monitored in the United Kingdom during the Second World War to gather intelligence information from occupied France.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] The line frequency was 11.025 kHz with vision broadcast at 46.0 MHz and sound at 42.0 MHz.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Aerials were independent for audio and vision at the top of the Eiffel tower, both vertically polarized.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] No gain being obtained from these pre-war basic aerials, the effective radiated power was only the transmitter's peak one, i.e.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] 30 kW which enabled a good reception in a radius of 100 km (62 miles) around Paris.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Frost's WRTH (World Radio TV Handbook) editions at that time, the transmitter's frequencies (42-46 MHz) were listed as channel "F1" or channel "S" (or "Special" channel) in the European Broadcasting Union's official documents.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Broadcasts were due to cease on January 1, 1958, as the 819 lines standard had been adopted in 1948 for the national network.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] However, after a long elections coverage night, most of the 441-line equipment was destroyed by fire on January 3, 1956.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] It was decided to indemnify the 3,000 owners of remaining 441-line sets and to entitle them to reduced rates for their new 819 lines receivers.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Following pre-war tests in 375 lines done by a Turin engineer named Arturo Castellani, broadcasts using the 441-line system began in Italy in 1939 with regular services from Rome using 2 kW power and Milan using 400 W of power in the frequency band of 40-45 MHz.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] As in France technical parameters – VHF frequencies excepted – were identical to those in use in Germany.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Broadcasts were discontinued on May 31, 1940.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] The first television tests in Japan were conducted as early as 1926 using a combined mechanical Nipkow disk and electronic Braun tube system, later switching to an all-electronic system in 1935 using a domestically developed iconoscope system.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Television broadcasting started on May 13, 1939, making the country one of the first in the world with an experimental television service.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] The broadcasts were in 441-lines with 25 frames/second and 4.5 MHz bandwidth.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] In spite of that, because of the beginning of World War II in the Pacific region, this first full-fledged TV broadcast experimentation lasted only a few months.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Regular television broadcasts would eventually start in 1953, using a modified version of the American 525-line standard.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] In September 1938 the Radio Manufacturers Association (RMA) recommended the 441-line system developed by RCA and Farnsworth Television.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Tests started a year before, in an attempt to perfect a 343-line system, with RCA executives petitioning the FCC for approval of their new standard.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] In early 1938 Philco's experimental transmitter W3XE in Philadelphia was already using the system.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] TV broadcasts were publicly launched in April 1939 by NBC, during the New York World's Fair, using the W2XBS station.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] The first pre-built TV receivers were sold on a very limited basis, mostly in New York City.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Manufacturers included RCA, General Electric, DuMont, and Andrea Radio Corporation.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] By June 1939, regularly scheduled broadcasts were available in New York and Los Angeles.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] By October nineteen TV broadcast licenses had been issued, including stations in New York, Philadelphia (W3XE), Chicago, Washington, Fort Wayne, Cincinnati, Schenectady (W2XB), Los Angeles and San Francisco.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] By November General Electric's station in Schenectady started broadcasts.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] W2XBS in New York broadcast up to fifty-eight hours of programming per month until December 1939, to an estimate of 2,000 receiving sets.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Reception area was a radius of 40-50 miles (80 km) from the Empire State Building.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Following a decision of the NTSC (National Television System Committee), the 525-line standard replaced the 441-line standard on July 1, 1941.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] In the Soviet Union a specification for a 441-line system using 50 interlaced fields per second was proposed in 1940.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Development of this system started in the 1930s, derived from test broadcasts from Moscow, using a 343-line system based on RCA equipment.
[src:serial-digital-interface/441-line-television-system] Due to World War II the 441-line system never reached the broadcast stage.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] The **455-line** standard, also known as 450-line, was a French black-and-white analog television broadcasting norm employed between 1937 and 1939.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] It was later replaced by the 441-line format, which remained in use until 1956.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] In 1931, in Paris, Georges Mandel, the Minister of Posts, provided support to the Compagnie des Compteurs (CdC) in conducting mechanical television experiments.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] Engineer René Barthélémy was granted a studio on Rue de Grenelle, Paris for this purpose.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] The resolution gradually increased from 30 to 60 lines and then to 180 lines by 1935, and the transmitter was located to the Eiffel Tower.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] Robert Jardillier, the next Minister of Posts, launched in 1936 a call for tenders to provide television with higher definition, based on the iconoscope and electronic television.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] A test period would follow and enable the best standard to be chosen.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] Broadcasts became regular from January 4, 1937, from 11 to 11:30 am and 8 to 8:30 pm on weekdays and from 5:30 pm to 7:30 pm on Sundays.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] Grammont performed its tests in 441 lines, the Compagnie Française de Télévision in 450 lines, and Thomson-Houston in 455 lines.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] In July 1937, the administration chose the 455-line system designed by Thomson-Houston, followed by public demonstrations at the International Exposition of Art and Technology in Modern Life.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] Broadcasts using the previous mechanical system continued alongside the new electronic system until April 10, 1938.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] In July 1938, a decree of the Posts, Telegraphs, and Telephones Agency defined the French terrestrial television standard as transmitting on 455 lines VHF (46 MHz, positive visual modulation, 25 frames per second), to be adopted throughout France within three years.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] 455-line TV sets from brands like Pathe-Marconi, Philips, Radioindustrie, CdC, Grammont, and Emyradio began to be sold to the public.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] In 1938, the transmitter, located at the Eiffel Tower, changed to this 455-line format, making it the most advanced and powerful broadcasting system in the world, boasting a transmission power of 30 kW.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] Radiodiffusion Nationale (RN Télévision) starts its broadcasts from Paris, and expansion for other cities like Lyon, Marseille and Bordeaux is planned.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] In the spring of 1939, tests are conducted in Lille.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] The Rue de Grenelle studio closed on July 31, 1939, and after this point, Radiodiffusion Nationale only broadcast films, documentaries, and recorded news using telecine.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] When France entered World War II on September 3, 1939, the military authorities ordered the cessation of broadcasts and took control of the Eiffel Tower transmitter.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] A few broadcasts were still broadcast episodically for transmitter maintenance purposes.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] On June 6, 1940, the French Resistance took action to sabotage this equipment to prevent its use by the Nazis.
[src:serial-digital-interface/455-line-television-system] However, in 1942, the occupying forces decided to repatriate the equipment for their Berlin station and replaced it with 441-line equipment.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Additional SDI standards have been introduced to support increasing video resolutions (HD, UHD and beyond), frame rates, stereoscopic (3D) video, and color depth.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] **Dual link HD-SDI** consists of a pair of SMPTE 292M links, standardized by SMPTE 372M in 1998; this provides a nominal 2.970 Gbit/s interface used in applications (such as digital cinema or HDTV 1080P) that require greater fidelity and resolution than standard HDTV can provide.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] **3G-SDI** (standardized in SMPTE 424M) consists of a single 2.970 Gbit/s serial link that allows replacing dual link HD-SDI.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] These standards are used for transmission of uncompressed, unencrypted digital video signals (optionally including embedded audio and time code) within television facilities; they can also be used for packetized data.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] SDI is used to connect together different pieces of equipment such as recorders, monitors, PCs and vision mixers.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Coaxial variants of the specification range in length but are typically less than 300 meters (980 ft).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Fiber optic variants of the specification such as 297M allow for long-distance transmission limited only by maximum fiber length or repeaters.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] SDI and HD-SDI are usually available only in professional video equipment because various licensing agreements restrict the use of unencrypted digital interfaces, such as SDI, prohibiting their use in consumer equipment.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Several professional video and HD-video capable DSLR cameras and all uncompressed video capable consumer cameras use the HDMI interface, often called clean HDMI.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] There are various mod kits for existing DVD players and other devices such as splitters that ignore HDCP, which allow a user to add a serial digital interface to these devices.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The various serial digital interface standards all use (one or more) coaxial cables with BNC connectors, with a nominal impedance of 75 ohms.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] This is the same type of cable used in analog composite video setups, potentially allowing for easier "drop-in" equipment upgrades (although, at high bitrates and/or long distances, it may be necessary for older, oxidising, or lower-grade cable to be replaced with optical fibre).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The specified signal amplitude at the source is 800 mV (±10%) peak-to-peak; far lower voltages may be measured at the receiver owing to attenuation.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Using equalization at the receiver, it is possible to send 270 Mbit/s SDI over 300 meters (980 ft) without use of repeaters, but shorter lengths are preferred.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The HD bitrates have a shorter maximum run length, typically 100 meters (330 ft).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Uncompressed digital component signals are transmitted.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Data is encoded in NRZI format, and a linear feedback shift register is used to scramble the data to reduce the likelihood that long strings of zeroes or ones will be present on the interface.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The interface is self-synchronizing and self-clocking.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Framing is done by detection of a special synchronization pattern, which appears on the (unscrambled) serial digital signal to be a sequence of ten ones followed by twenty zeroes (twenty ones followed by forty zeroes in HD); this bit pattern is not legal anywhere else within the data payload.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] SMPTE 297-2006 defines an optical fiber system for transmitting bit-serial digital signals.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In addition to optical specification, ST 297 also mandates laser safety testing and that all optical interfaces are labelled to indicate safety compliance, application and interoperability.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] An 8-bit parallel digital interface is defined by ITU-R Rec.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] 601; this is obsolete (however, many clauses in the various standards accommodate the possibility of an 8-bit interface).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In SD and ED applications, the serial data format is defined to 10 bits wide, whereas in HD applications, it is 20 bits wide, divided into two parallel 10-bit datastreams (known as **Y** and **C**).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] For all serial digital interfaces (excluding the obsolete composite encodings), the native color encoding is 4:2:2 YCbCr format.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The luminance channel (Y) is encoded at full bandwidth (13.5 MHz in 270 Mbit/s SD, ~75 MHz in HD), and the two chrominance channels (Cb and Cr) are subsampled horizontally and encoded at half bandwidth (6.75 MHz or 37.5 MHz).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The Y, Cr, and Cb samples are *co-sited* (acquired at the same instance in time), and the Y' sample is acquired at the time halfway between two adjacent Y samples.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In the above, Y refers to luminance samples, and C to chrominance samples.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Cr and Cb further refer to the red and blue "color difference" channels; see Component video for more information.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] This section only discusses the native color encoding of SDI; other color encodings are possible by treating the interface as a generic 10-bit data channel.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The use of other colorimetry encodings, and the conversion to and from RGB colorspace, is discussed below.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Video payload (as well as ancillary data payload) may use any 10-bit word in the range 4 to 1,019 (00416 to 3FB16) inclusive; the values 0–3 and 1,020–1,023 (3FC16–3FF16) are reserved and may not appear anywhere in the payload.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] These reserved words have two purposes; they are used both for Synchronization packets and for Ancillary data headers.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] A synchronization packet (commonly known as the **timing reference signal** or **TRS**) occurs immediately before the first active sample on every line, and immediately after the last active sample (and before the start of the horizontal blanking region).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The synchronization packet consists of four 10-bit words, the first three words are always the same—0x3FF, 0, 0; the fourth consists of 3 flag bits, along with an error correcting code.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] As a result, there are 8 different synchronization packets possible.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In the HD-SDI and dual link interfaces, synchronization packets *must* occur simultaneously in both the Y and C datastreams.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] (Some delay between the two cables in a dual link interface is permissible; equipment which supports dual link is expected to buffer the leading link in order to allow the other link to catch up).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In SD-SDI and enhanced definition interfaces, there is only one datastream, and thus only one synchronization packet at a time.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Other than the issue of how many packets appear, their format is the same in all versions of the serial-digital interface.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The flags bits found in the fourth word (commonly known as the **XYZ word**) are known as H, F, and V.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The H bit indicates the start of horizontal blank; and synchronization bits immediately preceding the horizontal blanking region must have H set to one.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Such packets are commonly referred to as **End of Active Video**, or **EAV** packets.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Likewise, the packet appearing immediately before the start of the active video has H set to 0; this is the **Start of Active Video** or **SAV** packet.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Likewise, the V bit is used to indicate the start of the vertical blanking region; an EAV packet with V=1 indicates the following line (lines are deemed to start at EAV) is part of the vertical interval, an EAV packet with V=0 indicates the following line is part of the active picture.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The F bit is used in interlaced and segmented-frame formats to indicate whether the line comes from the first or second field (or segment).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In progressive scan formats, the F bit is always set to zero.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In the high definition serial digital interface (and in dual-link HD), additional check words are provided to increase the robustness of the interface.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In these formats, the four samples immediately following the EAV packets (but not the SAV packets) contain a cyclic redundancy check field, and a line count indicator.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The CRC field provides a CRC of the preceding line (CRCs are computed independently for the Y and C streams) and can be used to detect bit errors in the interface.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The line count field indicates the line number of the current line.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The CRC and line counts are not provided in the SD and ED interfaces.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Instead, a special ancillary data packet known as an **EDH packet** may be optionally used to provide a CRC check on the data.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Each sample within a given datastream is assigned a unique line and sample number.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In all formats, the first sample immediately following the SAV packet is assigned sample number 0; the next sample is sample 1; all the way up to the XYZ word in the following SAV packet.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In SD interfaces, where there is only one datastream, the 0th sample is a Cb sample; the 1st sample a Y sample, the 2nd sample a Cr sample, and the third sample is the Y' sample; the pattern repeats from there.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In HD interfaces, each datastream has its own sample numbering—so the 0th sample of the Y datastream is the Y sample, the next sample the Y' sample, etc.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Likewise, the first sample in the C datastream is Cb, followed by Cr, followed by Cb again.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Lines are numbered sequentially, starting from 1, up to the number of lines per frame of the indicated format (typically 525, 625, 750, or 1125 (Sony HDVS)).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Determination of line 1 is somewhat arbitrary; however, it is unambiguously specified by the relevant standards.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In 525-line systems, the first line of vertical blank is line 1, whereas in other interlaced systems (625 and 1125-line), the first line after the F bit transitions to zero is line 1.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Note that lines are deemed to start at EAV, whereas sample zero is the sample following SAV.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] This produces the somewhat confusing result that the first sample in a given line of 1080i video is sample number 1920 (the first EAV sample in that format), and the line ends at the following sample 1919 (the last active sample in that format).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Note that this behavior differs somewhat from analog video interfaces, where the line transition is deemed to occur at the sync pulse, which occurs roughly halfway through the horizontal blanking region.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Link numbering is only an issue in multi-link interfaces.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The first link (the *primary* link) is assigned a link number of 1, subsequent links are assigned increasing link numbers; so, the second (*secondary*) link in a dual-link system is link 2.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The link number of a given interface is indicated by a VPID packet located in the vertical ancillary data space.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Note that the data layout in dual link is designed so that the primary link can be fed into a single-link interface, and still produce usable (though somewhat degraded) video.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The secondary link generally contains things like additional LSBs (in 12-bit formats), non-cosited samples in 4:4:4 sampled video (so that the primary link is still valid 4:2:2), and alpha or data channels.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] If the second link of a 1080P dual link configuration is absent, the first link still contains a valid 1080i signal.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In the case of 1080p60, 59.94, or 50 Hz video over a dual link; each link contains a valid 1080i signal at the same field rate.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The first link contains the 1st, 3rd, and 5th lines of odd fields and the 2nd, 4th, 6th, etc. lines of even fields, and the second link contains the even lines on the odd fields, and the odd lines on the even fields.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] When the two links are combined, the result is a progressive-scan picture at the higher frame rate.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Like SMPTE 259M, SMPTE 292M supports the SMPTE 291M standard for ancillary data.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Ancillary data is provided as a standardized transport for non-video payload within a serial digital signal; it is used for things such as embedded audio, closed captions, timecode, and other sorts of metadata.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Ancillary data is indicated by a 3-word packet consisting of 0, 3FF, 3FF (the opposite of the synchronization packet header), followed by a two-word identification code, a data count word (indicating 0–255 words of payload), the actual payload, and a one-word checksum.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Other than in their use in the header, the codes prohibited to video payload are also prohibited to ancillary data payload.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Specific applications of ancillary data include embedded audio, EDH, VPID and SDTI.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In dual link applications, ancillary data is mostly found on the primary link; the secondary link is to be used for ancillary data only if there is no room on the primary link.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] One exception to this rule is the VPID packet; both links must have a valid VPID packet present.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Both the HD and SD serial interfaces allow for 16 audio channels to be embedded along with the video.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The two interfaces use different audio encapsulation methods — SD uses the SMPTE 272M standard, whereas HD uses the SMPTE 299M standard.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Typically, 48 kHz, 24-bit (20-bit in SD, but extendable to 24 bit) PCM audio is encoded, in a manner directly compatible with the AES3 digital audio interface.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The data is placed in the horizontal blanking periods, when the SDI signal otherwise carries nothing useful (the receiver generates its own blanking signals from the TRS).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In dual-link applications, 32 channels of audio are available, as each link may carry 16 channels.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] SMPTE ST 299-2:2010 extends the 3G-SDI interface to be able to transmit 32 audio channels (16 pairs) on a single link.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] As the standard definition interface carries no checksum, CRC, or other data integrity check, an **EDH** (Error Detection and Handling) packet may be optionally placed in the vertical interval of the video signal.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] This packet includes CRC values for both the active picture, and the entire field (excluding those lines at which switching may occur, and which should contain no useful data); equipment can compute their own CRC and compare it with the received CRC in order to detect errors.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] EDH is typically only used with the standard definition interface; the presence of CRC words in the HD interface make EDH packets unnecessary.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] VPID (or video payload identifier) packets are increasingly used to describe the video format.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In early versions of the serial digital interface, it was always possible to uniquely determine the video format by counting the number of lines and samples between H and V transitions in the TRS.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] With the introduction of dual link interfaces, and segmented-frame standards, this is no longer possible; thus the VPID standard (defined by SMPTE 352M) provides a way to uniquely and unambiguously identify the format of the video payload.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The active portion of the video signal is defined to be those samples which follow an SAV packet and precede the next EAV packet; where the corresponding EAV and SAV packets have the V bit set to zero.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] It is in the active portion that the actual image information is stored.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Several color encodings are possible in the serial digital interface.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The default (and most common case) is 10-bit linearly sampled video data encoded as 4:2:2 YCbCr.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] (YCbCr is a digital representation of the YPbPr colorspace).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Samples of video are stored as described above.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Note that the scaling of the luma and chroma channels is *not* identical.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The minimum and maximum of these ranges represent the preferred signal limits, though the video payload may venture outside these ranges (providing that the reserved code words of 0–3 and 1020–1023 are *never* used for video payload).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In addition, the corresponding analog signal may have excursions further outside of this range.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] As YPbPr (and YCbCr) are both derived from the RGB colorspace, a means of converting is required.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] If an RGB encoding is used, the three primaries are all encoded in the same fashion as the Y channel; a value of 64 (40 hex) corresponds to 0 mV, and 940 (3AC hex) corresponds to 700 mV.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] 12-bit applications are scaled in a similar fashion to their 10-bit counterparts; the additional two bits are considered to be LSBs.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] For portions of the vertical and horizontal blanking regions which are not used for ancillary data, it is recommended that the luma samples be assigned the code word 64 (40 hex), and the chroma samples be assigned 512 (200 hex); both of which correspond to 0 mV.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] It is permissible to encode analog vertical interval information (such as vertical interval timecode or vertical interval test signals) without breaking the interface, but such usage is nonstandard (and ancillary data is the preferred means for transmitting metadata).
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Conversion of analog sync and burst signals into digital, however, is not recommended—and neither is necessary in the digital interface.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] Different picture formats have different requirements for digital blanking.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] For example, all so-called 1080-line HD formats have 1080 active lines, but 1125 total lines, with the remainder being vertical blanking.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] In addition to the regular serial digital interface described here, there are several other similar interfaces which are similar to, or are contained within, a serial digital interface.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] There is an expanded specification called SDTI (*Serial Data Transport Interface*), which allows compressed (i.e.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] DV, MPEG and others) video streams to be transported over an SDI line.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] This allows for multiple video streams in one cable or faster-than-realtime (2x, 4x,...) video transmission.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] A related standard, known as HD-SDTI, provides similar capability over an SMPTE 292M interface.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The SDTI interface is specified by SMPTE 305M.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The HD-SDTI interface is specified by SMPTE 348M.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The asynchronous serial interface (ASI) specification describes how to transport a MPEG Transport Stream (MPEG-TS), containing multiple MPEG video streams, over 75-ohm copper coaxial cable or multi-mode optical fiber.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] ASI is popular way to transport broadcast programs from the studio to the final transmission equipment before it reaches viewers sitting at home.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The ASI standard is part of the Digital Video Broadcasting (DVB) standard.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The standard *SMPTE 349M: Transport of Alternate Source Image Formats through SMPTE 292M*, specifies a means to encapsulate non-standard and lower-bitrate video formats within an HD-SDI interface.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] This standard allows, for example, several independent standard-definition video signals to be multiplexed onto an HD-SDI interface and transmitted down one wire.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The HDMI interface is a compact audio/video interface for transferring uncompressed video data and compressed/uncompressed digital audio data from an HDMI-compliant device to a compatible computer monitor, video projector, digital television, or digital audio device.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] It is mainly used in the consumer area, but increasingly used in professional devices including uncompressed video, often called clean HDMI.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The G.703 standard is another high-speed digital interface, originally designed for telephony.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The HDcctv standard embodies the adaptation of SDI for video surveillance applications, not to be confused with TDI, a similar but different format for video surveillance cameras.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The CoaXPress standard is another high-speed digital interface, originally designed for use with industrial cameras.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] The data rates for CoaXPress go up to 12.5 Gbit/s over a single coaxial cable.
[src:serial-digital-interface/serial-digital-interface] A 41 Mbit/s uplink channel and power over coax are also included in the standard.
